Thank you for writing, Mrs. Clancy. The security element on the back of the North Carolina driver license was discontinued on October 20, 2008. In the two years it was used, it added $.12 to the cost of each driver license, or about $720,000 over the two-year period. The $.12 per license was paid with DMV funds. The security element was established as a nationwide effort to identify driver licenses as manufactured by bona fide state agencies and to make them more difficult to counterfeit. The element was designed by motor vehicle administrators from throughout the country to assist law enforcement, and others who might need to check driver licenses, in identifying and verifying the license as one issued legally.  It was also a way for all license-issuing agencies throughout the country to carry a security element on licenses that was common to all of them. After the pilot project by North Carolina, the group (the American Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators) decided not to take the program nationwide. The group, as well as the North Carolina Division of Motor Vehicles, continue to be concerned with strengthening the security of the driver licenses we issue. 

