Mr. Howell,
The Governor asked that I respond to your question regarding inspection requirements for certain vehicles.
In the late 1980s, Congress was wrestling with the increasing nationwide problem of Air Pollution. The number of vehicles traveling on the nations highways was rapidly increasing, and there were warnings of dwindling oil reserves. In an effort to combat these problems, the Clean Air Act of 1990 was enacted. The Clean Air Act gave the U.S. Protection Agency (EPA) the responsibility for developing and implementing a Mobile Source Emission Reduction Program. This program pursues a three point strategy for reducing emissions from transportation sources. The first two points involve the development and commercialization of cleaner vehicles and cleaner fuels. The third point focuses on in-use control to ensure that cars in customer use are properly maintained.
As part of this strategy, the EPA requires On-Board Diagnostic (OBD) system checks as a component of inspection programs. Although OBD is not new to vehicle manufacturers, it was not standardized to allow for this type of testing on all vehicles until 1996. Because OBD testing cannot be conducted on 1995 and older vehicles, and the EPA determined that these model years make up such a small percentage of the motoring population, with continued reduction each year, there was no need to require emissions testing on these vehicles.

As previously indicated, the EPA recognizes the benefits of cleaner vehicles and encourages development and use nationwide. However, if not properly maintained, these vehicles can also contribute to air pollution. Therefore, the EPA requires all 1996 and newer vehicles to receive periodic testing.

I trust this information was useful. If I can be of further assistance, please advise.

David

